	<div class="row">
		<div class="col-md-10 col-centered">
			<a name="solution"><h3>Solution</h3></a>			
			<p>
				The purpose achieved by the iWatch was to highlight events that required the most attention, and specifically to notify users of the latest communication from their important contacts. We fulfilled this objective by making the home screen an event log that was people- based. This “timeline” became the most important screen and was placed in the beginning of the app, helping narrow down the users’ choices in navigating to the next screens.
			</p>
			<div class="col-md-8 col-md-offset-2">
				<p>
					On the phone app, if I was looking for any missed communication from my boss, Jane Smith, I would have to check either the “Messages” or “Call Log” section to look through a list of names. In this flow, I would have to first search by communication type, and then for a person’s name.
				</p>

				<div class="col-md-4 col-md-offset-1">
					<img src="/images/projects/iwatch-project/13-most-recent-messages.png">
				</div>
				<div class="col-md-4">
					<img src="/images/projects/iwatch-project/14-most-recent-calls.png">
				</div>
			</div>
		</div>
	</div>

	<div class="row">
		<div class="col-md-10 col-centered">
			<p>
				On the watch app, users would most likely find the latest communication with a contact most important and relevant, so we decided to shift away from the paradigm used on the phone. Instead of separating notifications by communication type, we grouped them by contact person in the events timeline.
			</p>
			<div class="col-md-8 col-md-offset-2">
				<p>Ability to drill down into the log of events with a contact</p>
				<img src="/images/projects/iwatch-project/15-watch-homescreen.png">
			</div>
			<div class="col-md-8 col-md-offset-2">
				<p>Ability to view the latest communication by contact person</p>
				<img src="/images/projects/iwatch-project/16-events-listed-by-people.png">
				<p>
					On the watch app, instead of checking either a “Messages” or a “Calls” section first, I could immediately see upon opening the app if Jane was trying to reach me. Here, I could see in one glance that I had three new events from her, including a missed call at 4:35pm.
				</p>
			</div>
			<div class="col-md-10">
				<p>
					From the home screen, users could immediately decide whether they wanted to view more details and take action. This design optimized a way to navigate through workflows with the fewest number of taps in a minimal amount of space.
				</p>
			</div>
			<div class="col-md-8 col-md-offset-2">
				<img src="/images/projects/iwatch-project/17-wireframe-flow.png">
				<p>
					By designing the timeline to be people-based, we created an easy way for users to quickly see whether they had any missed notifications, and who tried to reach them.
				</p>
